x4freetext: University electron storage ring using High-Intensity
filled with BC-501A scintillator was used to detect
neutrons generated from photofission. Diameter of
each detector was 12.7 cm and thickness was 5.1 cm.
Twelve detectors were placed at theta = 55deg, 90deg
270deg. Six detectors were placed at theta = 72deg,
target was positioned at the center of the array, and
the flight path from the target to each detector was
Time of flight was used to determine
neutron energy. Pulse shape discrimination was used
from relativistic electrons in one of the two
straight sections of electron storage ring. HIgS
facility is a nearly-monoenergetic Compton gamma-ray
source with a wide energy range and switchable
linear and circular polarizations.For this experiment,
the FEL wavelength was 540 nm and
the electron beam energies were selected to produce
gamma-ray beams between 5.6 and 7.3 MeV, with an
energy spread (FWHM) of 3%. The gamma-ray beams were
produced having either circular or linear
polarizations. Because of the duty factor of the
electron storage ring, the gamma-ray beam is pulsed
with a period of 179 ns. The temporal structure of the
gamma-ray beam made possible the use of a
time-of-flight method to determine neutron energies.
